{"title_page": "Anton\u00edn Baudy\u0161", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Infobox Minister\n| name = Anton\u00edn Baudy\u0161\n| image   = A Baudys 2010.jpg\n| imagesize = \n| caption = A. Baudys in 2010\n| office = [[Ministry of Defence (Czech Republic)|Minister of Defense]]\n| primeminister =[[V\u00e1clav Klaus]]\n| predecessor = ''Office established''\n| successor =Vilem Holan\n| term_start =January 1993\n| term_end = 22 September 1994\n| office1 = Deputy Prime Minister\n| primeminister1=\n| predecessor1 =\n| successor1 =\n| term_start1 = 1989\n| term_end1= July 1992\n| birth_date =9 September 1946\n| birth_place =[[Prague]]\n| death_date = 24 August 2010 (aged 63)\n| death_place      = \n| restingplace     = \n| party = [[Czechoslovak People's Party]]<br/> [[Christian Democratic Union - Czechoslovak People's Party]]\n| residence = \n| alma_mater =[[Czech Technical University in Prague|Czech Technical University]]\n| spouse = \n| nationality = [[Czechs|Czech]]\n| religion= \n| children = \n| website =\n}}\n\n'''Anton\u00edn Baudy\u0161''' (9 September 1946 &ndash; 24 August 2010) was a [[Czechs|Czech]] academic and politician who served as defense minister from 1993 to 1994. He was the first defense minister of [[the Czech Republic]].<ref name=Ulrich1999>{{cite book|author=Marybeth Peterson Ulrich|title=Democratizing Communist Militaries: The Cases of the Czech and Russian Armed Forces|url=http://www.press.umich.edu/pdf/0472109693-03.pdf|accessdate=26 August 2013|year=1999|publisher=University of Michigan Press|isbn=978-0-472-10969-2|page=85}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nBaudy\u0161 was born in [[Prague]] on 9 September 1946.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Brokl|first=Lubomir|author2=Zdenka Mansfeldov\u00e1|title=Czech Republic|journal=European Journal of Political Research|date=December 1994|volume=26|issue=3\u20134|pages=269\u2013277|doi=10.1111/j.1475-6765.1994.tb00446.x}}</ref><ref name=eiwire/> He studied mechanical engineering<ref name=Ulrich1999/> and graduated from [[Czech Technical University in Prague|the Czech Technical University]] (CVUT).<ref name=eiwire/>\n\n==Career==\nBaudy\u0161 worked as a university professor at his alma mater, CVUT, until 1989.<ref name=Ulrich1999/><ref name=eiwire/> He became a member of [[Czechoslovak People's Party|the Czechoslovak People's Party]] (CSL) in 1970.<ref name=eiwire/> He was named deputy prime minister in 1989 shortly after the fall of communist regime and held the post until July 1992.<ref name=eiwire/> He was appointed defense minister to [[V\u00e1clav Klaus' First Cabinet|the coalition cabinet]] led by Prime Minister [[V\u00e1clav Klaus]] in January 1993.<ref>{{cite book|author=Andrew A. Michta|title=America's New Allies: Poland, Hungary, and the Czech Republic in NATO|url=https://archive.org/details/americasnewallie00mich|url-access=registration|accessdate=26 August 2013|date=1 January 1999|publisher=University of Washington Press|isbn=978-0-295-80376-0|page=[https://archive.org/details/americasnewallie00mich/page/135 135]}}</ref> The ministry was formed with his appointment.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Vesselin Dimitrov|author2=Klaus H. Goetz|author3=Hellmut Wollmann|title=Governing After Communism: Institutions and Policymaking|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6zMLJe-jsUsC&pg=PA131|accessdate=26 August 2013|year=2006|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=978-0-7425-4009-5|pages=131}}</ref> He was a member of [[Christian Democratic Union - Czechoslovak People's Party|the Christian Democratic Union-Czechoslovak People's Party]] (KDU-CSL).<ref>{{cite news|title=Sacked Defense Minister Opens Old Wounds |url=http://www.praguepost.com/archivescontent/17004-sacked-defense-minister-opens-old-wounds.html |accessdate=26 August 2013 |newspaper=The Prague Post |date=28 September 1994 |author=Tomas Kellner|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130826072008/http://www.praguepost.com/archivescontent/17004-sacked-defense-minister-opens-old-wounds.html|archivedate=August 26, 2013}}</ref> On 22 September 1994, [[Vil\u00e9m Hol\u00e1\u0148]] of KDU-CSL replaced Baudy\u0161 in the post.<ref>{{cite book|author=Jeffrey Simon|title=NATO Enlargement and Central Europe: A Study in Civil-military Relations|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cS8TIsg1Kg4C&pg=PA221|accessdate=26 August 2013|year=1996|publisher=DIANE Publishing|isbn=978-1-4289-8158-4|page=221}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his removal from office, he worked as a businessman<ref>{{cite news|title=Czechs Say They Warned U.S. of Chemical Weapons in Gulf|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/10/19/us/czechs-say-they-warned-us-of-chemical-weapons-in-gulf.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm|accessdate=26 August 2013|newspaper=The New York Times|date=19 October 1996|author=Philip Shenon}}</ref> and a popular astrologist.<ref name=eiwire/>\n\n===Activities===\nOne of his first activities as defense minister was to initiate the cleansing of the society from hard-liner communists and informers.<ref name=Ulrich1999/> He stated his aim as defense minister to transform the ministry into \"an integrated civilian-military institution\".<ref>{{cite book|author1=Natalie Mychajlyszyn|author2=Harald Von Riekhoff|title=The Evolution of Civil-military Relations in East-Central Europe and the Former Soviet Union|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IYApYztRK1wC&pg=PA52|accessdate=26 August 2013|date=1 January 2004|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-313-31562-6|page=52}}</ref> During his tenure Baudy\u0161 was informed that the Czech army had had [[pathogens]].<ref name=wh2009/> He ordered the destruction of them due to the fact that they were no longer necessary.<ref name=wh2009>{{cite book|author1=Mark Wheelis|author2=Lajos R\u00f3zsa|title=Deadly Cultures: Biological Weapons since 1945|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fj7aU0qzTLYC&pg=PA162|accessdate=26 August 2013|date=30 June 2009|publisher=Harvard University Press|isbn=978-0-674-04513-2|page=162}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life and death==\nBaudy\u0161 married twice. He had two sons from his first marriage.<ref name=eiwire/> In May 2010, he divorced his first wife and married a woman who was 23 years younger than him.<ref name=eiwire/>\n\nHe died at age 63 on 24 August 2010.<ref name=eiwire>{{cite news|title=Baudys held high posts in Czechoslovak, Czech govts in 1990s|url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/article-1G1-235619535/baudys-held-high-posts.html|accessdate=26 August 2013|work=Europe Intelligence Wire|date=24 August 2010|agency=Czech News Agency|location=Prague}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n\n{{CZ-D-ministers}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baudys, Antonin}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:2010 deaths]]\n[[Category:KDU-\u010cSL Government ministers]]\n[[Category:Czech academics]]\n[[Category:Czech engineers]]\n[[Category:Czech Technical University in Prague alumni]]\n[[Category:Czech Technical University in Prague faculty]]\n[[Category:Czech businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Defence ministers of the Czech Republic]]\n[[Category:People from Prague]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Prague]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Infobox Minister\n| name = Anton\u00edn Baudy\u0161\n| image   = A Baudys 2010.jpg\n| imagesize = \n| caption = A. Baudys in 2010\n| office = [[Ministry of Defence (Czech Republic)|Minister of Defense]]\n| primeminister =[[V\u00e1clav Klaus]]\n| predecessor = ''Office established''\n| successor =Vilem Holan\n| term_start =January 1993\n| term_end = 22 September 1994\n| office1 = Deputy Prime Minister\n| primeminister1=\n| predecessor1 =\n| successor1 =\n| term_start1 = 1989\n| term_end1= July 1992\n| birth_date =9 September 1946\n| birth_place =[[Prague]]\n| death_date = 24 August 2010 (aged 63)\n| death_place      = \n| restingplace     = \n| party = [[Czechoslovak People's Party]]<br/> [[Christian Democratic Union - Czechoslovak People's Party]]\n| residence = \n| alma_mater =[[Czech Technical University in Prague|Czech Technical University]]\n| spouse = \n| nationality = [[Czechs|Czech]]\n| religion= \n| children = \n| website =\n}}\n\n'''Anton\u00edn Baudy\u0161''' (9 September 1946 &ndash; 24 August 2010) was a [[Czechs|Czech]] academic and politician who served as defense minister from 1993 to 1994. He was the first defense minister of [[the Czech Republic]].<ref name=Ulrich1999>{{cite book|author=Marybeth Peterson Ulrich|title=Democratizing Communist Militaries: The Cases of the Czech and Russian Armed Forces|url=http://www.press.umich.edu/pdf/0472109693-03.pdf|accessdate=26 August 2013|year=1999|publisher=University of Michigan Press|isbn=978-0-472-10969-2|page=85}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nBaudy\u0161 was born in [[Prague]] on 9 September 1946.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Brokl|first=Lubomir|author2=Zdenka Mansfeldov\u00e1|title=Czech Republic|journal=European Journal of Political Research|date=December 1994|volume=26|issue=3\u20134|pages=269\u2013277|doi=10.1111/j.1475-6765.1994.tb00446.x}}</ref><ref name=eiwire/> He studied mechanical engineering<ref name=Ulrich1999/> and graduated from [[Czech Technical University in Prague|the Czech Technical University]] (CVUT).<ref name=eiwire/>\n\n==Career==\nBaudy\u0161 worked as a university professor at his alma mater, CVUT, until 1989.<ref name=Ulrich1999/><ref name=eiwire/> He became a member of [[Czechoslovak People's Party|the Czechoslovak People's Party]] (CSL) in 1970.<ref name=eiwire/> He was named deputy prime minister in 1989 shortly after the fall of communist regime and held the post until July 1992.<ref name=eiwire/> He was appointed defense minister to [[V\u00e1clav Klaus' First Cabinet|the coalition cabinet]] led by Prime Minister [[V\u00e1clav Klaus]] in January 1993.<ref>{{cite book|author=Andrew A. Michta|title=America's New Allies: Poland, Hungary, and the Czech Republic in NATO|url=https://archive.org/details/americasnewallie00mich|url-access=registration|accessdate=26 August 2013|date=1 January 1999|publisher=University of Washington Press|isbn=978-0-295-80376-0|page=[https://archive.org/details/americasnewallie00mich/page/135 135]}}</ref> The ministry was formed with his appointment.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Vesselin Dimitrov|author2=Klaus H. Goetz|author3=Hellmut Wollmann|title=Governing After Communism: Institutions and Policymaking|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6zMLJe-jsUsC&pg=PA131|accessdate=26 August 2013|year=2006|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=978-0-7425-4009-5|pages=131}}</ref> He was a member of [[Christian Democratic Union - Czechoslovak People's Party|the Christian Democratic Union-Czechoslovak People's Party]] (KDU-CSL).<ref>{{cite news|title=Sacked Defense Minister Opens Old Wounds |url=http://www.praguepost.com/archivescontent/17004-sacked-defense-minister-opens-old-wounds.html |accessdate=26 August 2013 |newspaper=The Prague Post |date=28 September 1994 |author=Tomas Kellner|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130826072008/http://www.praguepost.com/archivescontent/17004-sacked-defense-minister-opens-old-wounds.html|archivedate=August 26, 2013}}</ref> On 22 September 1994, Vilem Holan of KDU-CSL replaced Baudy\u0161 in the post.<ref>{{cite book|author=Jeffrey Simon|title=NATO Enlargement and Central Europe: A Study in Civil-military Relations|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cS8TIsg1Kg4C&pg=PA221|accessdate=26 August 2013|year=1996|publisher=DIANE Publishing|isbn=978-1-4289-8158-4|page=221}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his removal from office, he worked as a businessman<ref>{{cite news|title=Czechs Say They Warned U.S. of Chemical Weapons in Gulf|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/10/19/us/czechs-say-they-warned-us-of-chemical-weapons-in-gulf.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm|accessdate=26 August 2013|newspaper=The New York Times|date=19 October 1996|author=Philip Shenon}}</ref> and a popular astrologist.<ref name=eiwire/>\n\n===Activities===\nOne of his first activities as defense minister was to initiate the cleansing of the society from hard-liner communists and informers.<ref name=Ulrich1999/> He stated his aim as defense minister to transform the ministry into \"an integrated civilian-military institution\".<ref>{{cite book|author1=Natalie Mychajlyszyn|author2=Harald Von Riekhoff|title=The Evolution of Civil-military Relations in East-Central Europe and the Former Soviet Union|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IYApYztRK1wC&pg=PA52|accessdate=26 August 2013|date=1 January 2004|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-313-31562-6|page=52}}</ref> During his tenure Baudy\u0161 was informed that the Czech army had had [[pathogens]].<ref name=wh2009/> He ordered the destruction of them due to the fact that they were no longer necessary.<ref name=wh2009>{{cite book|author1=Mark Wheelis|author2=Lajos R\u00f3zsa|title=Deadly Cultures: Biological Weapons since 1945|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fj7aU0qzTLYC&pg=PA162|accessdate=26 August 2013|date=30 June 2009|publisher=Harvard University Press|isbn=978-0-674-04513-2|page=162}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life and death==\nBaudy\u0161 married twice. He had two sons from his first marriage.<ref name=eiwire/> In May 2010, he divorced his first wife and married a woman who was 23 years younger than him.<ref name=eiwire/>\n\nHe died at age 63 on 24 August 2010.<ref name=eiwire>{{cite news|title=Baudys held high posts in Czechoslovak, Czech govts in 1990s|url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/article-1G1-235619535/baudys-held-high-posts.html|accessdate=26 August 2013|work=Europe Intelligence Wire|date=24 August 2010|agency=Czech News Agency|location=Prague}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n\n{{CZ-D-ministers}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baudys, Antonin}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:2010 deaths]]\n[[Category:KDU-\u010cSL Government ministers]]\n[[Category:Czech academics]]\n[[Category:Czech engineers]]\n[[Category:Czech Technical University in Prague alumni]]\n[[Category:Czech Technical University in Prague faculty]]\n[[Category:Czech businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Defence ministers of the Czech Republic]]\n[[Category:People from Prague]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Prague]]\n", "name_user": "Buidhe", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer:link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anton%C3%ADn_Baudy%C5%A1"}
{"title_page": "1989 Asia Golf Circuit", "text_new": "{{use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\nThe '''1989 Asia Golf Circuit''' was the 28th season of [[golf]] tournaments that comprised the [[Asia Golf Circuit]].\n\nAmerican [[Brian Claar]] claimed the overall circuit championship.\n\n==Tournament schedule==\nThe table below shows the 1989 Asia Golf Circuit schedule.<ref>{{cite book |title=World of Professional Golf 1990 |first=Mark H. |last=McCormack |authorlink=Mark McCormack |publisher=Sackville |date=1990 |page=276\u2013284, 516\u2013527 |isbn=0948615389}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/44378544/1989-asia-golf-circuit/ |title=1989 Asia Golf Circuit |newspaper=Tampa Bay Times |location=St.Petersburg,Florida |date=31 March 1989 |page=29 |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> For the first time, the circuit had eleven tournaments with the addition of the [[Pakistan Open]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:95%\"\n!Date!!Tournament!!Country!!Prize<br/>fund ([[US$]])!!Winner!!Notes!!Refs\n|-\n|9\u201312 Feb || [[Philippine Open (golf)|San Miguel/Coca-Cola Philippine Open]] || Philippines || align=right|140,000  || {{flagicon|USA}} [[Emlyn Aubrey]] ||  ||  <ref>{{cite news |url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Page/straitstimes19890213-1.1.31 |title=First win |newspaper=The Straits Times |location=Singapore |date=13 February 1989 |page=31 |via=National Library Board |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news |url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Page/straitstimes19890214-1.1.31 |title=Scores |newspaper=The Straits Times |location=Singapore |date=14 February 1989 |page=31 |via=National Library Board |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|16\u201319 Feb|| [[Hong Kong Open (golf)|Johnnie Walker Hong Kong Open]] || Hong Kong || align=right|175,000 || {{flagicon|USA}} [[Brian Claar]] ||  || <ref>{{cite news |url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Page/straitstimes19890220-1.1.29|title=Claar's gift for his lucky wife|newspaper=The Straits Times |location=Singapore |date=20 February 1989 |page=29 |via=National Library Board  |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|23\u201326 Feb || [[Thailand Open (golf)|Thai International Thailand Open]] || Thailand || align=right|150,000 || {{flagicon|USA|}} [[Brian Claar]] ||  || <ref>{{cite news |url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Page/straitstimes19890227-1.1.30 |title=Claar adds Thai Open to his double |newspaper=The Straits Times |location=Singapore |date=28 March 1989 |accessdate=9 April 2020|page=30 |via=National Library Board}}</ref>\n|-\n|2\u20135 Mar || [[Pakistan Open]] || Pakistan || align=right|120,000 || {{flagicon|PHI}} [[Frankie Mi\u00f1oza]] || New tournament; held the same week as the [[Rolex Masters]]. ||  <ref>{{cite news |url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Page/straitstimes19890317-1.1.27 |title=World at a glance  |newspaper=New Straits Times |location=Malaysia |date=7 March 1989 |page=19 |via=Google  Archive|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|9\u201312 Mar ||[[Indian Open (golf)|Wills Indian Open]] || India || align=right|120,000 || {{flagicon|CAN}} [[R\u00e9my Bouchard]] ||  ||  <ref>{{cite news |url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Page/biztimes19890313-1.1.27 |title=Bouchard clinches Indian Open title |newspaper=The Business Times |location=Singapore |date=13 March 1989 |page=27|via=National Library Board |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|16\u201319 Mar || [[Singapore Open (golf)|Singapore Open]] || Singapore || align=right|220,000 || {{flagicon|TWN}} [[Lu Chien-soon]] ||  ||  <ref>{{cite news |url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Page/straitstimes19890320-1.1.34 |title=Chien-soon gets his second win |newspaper=The Straits Times |location=Singapore |date=20 March 1989 |page=34 |via=National Library Board |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|22\u201325 Mar || [[Indonesia Open (golf)|Indonesian Open]] || Indonesia || align=right|120,000 || {{flagicon|INA}} [[Kasiyadi]] || || <ref>{{cite news |url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Page/straitstimes19890320-1.1.20 |title=Hero Kasiyadi is home and dry |newspaper=The Straits Times |location=Singapore |date=26 March 1989 |page=20 |via=National Library Board |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|30 Mar \u2013 2 Apr || [[Malaysian Open (golf)|Benson & Hedges Malaysian Open]] || Malaysia || align=right|175,000 || {{flagicon|USA|}} [[Jeff Maggert]] ||  || <ref>{{cite news |url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Page/straitstimes19890403-1.1.38 |title=Maggert drought breaks in the rain |newspaper=The Straits Times |location=Singapore |date=3 April 1989 |accessdate=30 March 2020|page=38 |via=National Library Board}}</ref>\n|- \n|6\u20139 Apr || [[Taiwan Open (golf)|Republic of China Open]] || Taiwan || align=right|200,000 || {{flagicon|TWN|}} [[Lu Chien-soon]] ||  ||  <ref>{{cite news |url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Page/straitstimes19890410-1.1.30 |title=Lu takes title |newspaper=The Straits Times |location=Singapore |date=11 April 1989 |page=30 |via=National Library Board |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|13\u201316 Apr || [[Maekyung Open]] || South Korea || align=right|150,000 || {{flagicon|TWN}} [[Lu Hsi-chuen]] ||  || <ref>{{cite news |url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Page/straitstimes19890417-1.1.35 |title=Hsi-chuen is Korean Champion |newspaper=The Straits Times |location=Singapore |date=17 April 1989 |page=35|via=National Library Board |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|20\u201323 Apr|| [[Dunlop International Open]] || Japan || align=right|[[Japanese yen|\u00a5]]60,000,000 || {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Terry Gale]] ||  ||  <ref>{{cite news |url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Page/straitstimes19890424-1.1.39 |title=Gale winds up the winner |newspaper=The Straits Times |location=Singapore |date=24 April 1989 |page=39|via=National Library Board |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Final standings==\nThe Asia Golf Circuit operated a points based system to determine the overall circuit champion, with points being awarded in each tournament to the leading players. At the end of the season, the player with the most points was declared the circuit champion, and there was a prize pool to be shared between the top players in the points table.\n{|class=wikitable\n|-\n!#!!Player!!Points <ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=LqclAAAAIBAJ&sjid=kQsEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6237%2C4368601|title=Minoza 4th in Asian Order of merit|newspaper=Manila Standard |location=Philippines |date=24 April 1989 |page=12|via=Google Archive |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1 || {{flagicon|USA}} [[Brian Claar]] ||  align=center|882\n|-\n| 2 || {{flagicon|USA}} [[Emlyn Aubrey]] || align=center|732\n|-\n| 3 || {{flagicon|MEX}} [[Carlos Espinosa (golfer)|Carlos Espinosa]] ||  align=center|682\n|-\n| 4 || {{flagicon|PHI}} [[Frankie Mi\u00f1oza]] || align=center|638\n|-\n| 5 || {{flagicon|TWN}} [[Lu Chien-soon]] || align=center|595\n|-\n| 6 || {{flagicon|TWN}} [[Lu Hsi-chuen]] || align=center|595\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Asia Golf Circuit seasons}}\n\n[[Category:1989 in golf|Asia Golf Circuit]]\n[[Category:Asia Golf Circuit]]\n", "text_old": "{{use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\nThe '''1989 Asia Golf Circuit''' was the 28th season of [[golf]] tournaments that comprised the [[Asia Golf Circuit]].\n\nAmerican [[Brian Claar]] claimed the overall circuit championship.\n\n==Tournament schedule==\nThe table below shows the 1989 Asia Golf Circuit schedule.<ref>{{cite book |title=World of Professional Golf 1990 |first=Mark H. |last=McCormack |authorlink=Mark McCormack |publisher=Sackville |date=1990 |page=276\u2013284, 516\u2013527 |isbn=0948615389}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/44378544/1989-asia-golf-circuit/ |title=1989 Asia Golf Circuit |newspaper=