entury New Zealand painters]]\n[[Category:Women watercolorists]]\n[[Category:Landscape painters]]\n[[Category:People from Nelson, New Zealand]]\n[[Category:New Zealand women illustrators]]\n[[Category:20th-century New Zealand artists]]\n[[Category:19th-century New Zealand artists]]\n[[Category:19th-century New Zealand women artists]]\n[[Category:20th-century New Zealand women artists]]\n[[Category:Burials at Richmond Cemetery, New Zealand]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name             = Nina Jones\n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name       = Nina Lucy Mary Jones\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|1871|06|22|df=yes}} \n| birth_place      = [[Christchurch]], New Zealand\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|1926|02|08|1871|06|22|df=yes}} \n| death_place      = [[Nelson, New Zealand|Nelson]], New Zealand\n| resting_place    = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| residence        = \n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = \n| known_for        = Botanical paintings\n| notable_works    = \n| style            = Watercolour\n| movement         = \n| spouse           = \n| partner          = \n| awards           = \n| elected          = \n| patrons          = \n| memorials        = \n| website          = \n| module           = \n}}\n'''Nina Lucy Mary Jones''' (22 June 1871 \u2013 8 February 1926) was an artist and botanical illustrator from Nelson, New Zealand.\n\n==Biography==\nNina Jones was born in the [[Christchurch]] suburb of [[St Martins, New Zealand|St Martins]] to Eliza and Charles Jones,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/LT18710624.2.7 |title=Births |work=Lyttelton Times |date=24 June 1871 |accessdate=13 June 2019 |page=2}}</ref> before moving to [[Nelson, New Zealand|Nelson]] with her parents where she remained for the rest of her life. She was a water colourist who primarily painted landscapes and botanical paintings, and exhibited widely at New Zealand's local Art Society's exhibitions. For a time she also worked with metal and had examples of her work exhibited in a show held in Christchurch to celebrate [[Queen Victoria]]'s jubilee.<ref>{{cite news |work=Evening Star |title=The Canterbury exhibition |url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/ESD19001206.2.16 |accessdate=14 April 2019 |date=6 December 1900 |page=2}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Calhoun |first1=Ann |title=The Arts & Crafts Movement in New Zealand, 1870\u20131940: Women Make Their Mark |date=2000 |publisher=Auckland University Press |page=126}}</ref> Botanists from around New Zealand sent her samples to paint, a newspaper article of the time stated, \"The amount of careful labour, the trueness of colour and regard to the habits of these bush flowers as well as the artistic perception of the artist must speak to all lovers of New Zealand native flora.\"<ref>{{cite news |work=Nelson Evening Mail |url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NEM19261101.2.43 |title=Art gallery: Nina Jones' exhibition |page=4 |accessdate=14 April 2019 |date=1 November 1926}}</ref>\n\nJones was involved in the arts both locally and nationally. She was involved in the Suter Arts Society since its inception in 1899. This was previously known as the Bishopdate Sketching Club of which she was also a member and secretary (1899\u20131925).<ref>{{cite web |title=Nelson Suter Arts Society |url=http://www.theprow.org.nz/yourstory/nelson-suter-art-society/ |accessdate=14 April 2019 |first=Ellie |last=Holland |website=The Prow}}</ref> Jones was involved in the National Arts Society as the Nelson vice president.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Kirker |first1=Anna |title=New Zealand Women Artists: A Survey of 150 Years |date=1986 |publisher=Reed Methuen |location=Auckland |page=58}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |work=Nelson Evening Mail |url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NEM19250617.2.38 |title=Suter Art Society |page=6 |accessdate=14 April 2019 |date=17 June 1925}}</ref>\n\nJones was requested by the [[New Zealand Government]] to submit 30 of her paintings of native flowers and fruits to be exhibited at the [[British Empire Exhibition]] at Wembley in 1924\u201325.<ref>{{cite news |work=Manawatu Standard |title=Women's notes |url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/MS19251219.2.76 |accessdate=14 April 2019 |page=11 |date=19 December 1925}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Phillips |first1=Jock |title=British Empire Exhibition, Wembley, 1924\u201325 |url=https://teara.govt.nz/en/exhibitions-and-worlds-fairs/print |website=Te Ara |accessdate=14 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite news |work=Nelson Evening Mail |title=Obituary: Miss Nina Jones |url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NEM19260209.2.26 |accessdate=14 April 2019 |date=9 February 1926 |page=4}}</ref>\n\nJones exhibited at [[Canterbury Society of Arts]] and [[New Zealand Academy of Fine Arts]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://findnzartists.org.nz/artist/7972/nina-lucy-mary-jones|title=Jones, Nina Lucy Mary|website=Find New Zealand Artists: a database of artist names |accessdate=16 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nJones died on 8 February 1926 at her home in Franklyn Rise, Nelson, and was buried in [[Richmond, New Zealand|Richmond]] Cemetery on 9 February 1926.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{cite web |title=Cemetery record for Nina Jones |url=https://ce.tasman.govt.nz/cemeteries/plot_records/05206 |publisher=Tasman District Council |accessdate=14 April 2019}}</ref> After her death, Jones's works were left in trust to the people of Nelson and they are now held in the [[Nelson Provincial Museum]].<ref>{{Cite news |title=Old paintings resurrected |date=14 December 1979| work=Nelson Evening Mail}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collection.nelsonmuseum.co.nz/objects?query=%22Nina+Jones%22&limit=21&hasImages=true|title=Nina Jones|last=|first=|date=|publisher=Nelson Provincial Museum |access-date=14 April 2019}}</ref> \n\n==Legacy==\nAn exhibition celebrating her career as an artist was held at the [[Suter Gallery]] in October 1926 and showed nearly 250 of her paintings. A review of the exhibition stated, \"The exhibition was of a much more extensive and comprehensive nature than most folks anticipated. The fine artistic touch, noticeable in every picture shown, was greatly admired. The collection is unique and the artist's work is destined to be of much value for all time to come.\"<ref>{{cite news |work=Nelson Evening Mail |url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NEM19261108.2.35 |title=Local and general |page=4 |accessdate=14 April 2019 |date=8 November 1926}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nImage:Earina by Nina Lucy Mary Jones.jpg|Earina\nImage:(Unknown) by Nina Jones ac118.jpg|(Unknown)\nImage:Pimelea traversii by Nina Jones ac114.jpg|Pimelea\nImage:(Rubus) by Nina Jones ac103.jpg|Rubus\nImage:Rubus by Nina Jones ac94.jpg|Rubus\nImage:(Epilobium) by Nina Jones ac122.jpg|Epilobium\nImage:(Olearia insignis) by Nina Jones ac127.jpg|Olearia insignis\nImage:Nothofagus solanderi by Nina Jones ac124.jpg|Nothofagus solanderi\nImage:Parsonsia by Nina Jones ac96.jpg|Parsonsia\nImage:(Unknown) by Nina Jones ac121.jpg|Unknown\nImage:Coprosma acerosa by Nina Jones ac139.jpg|Coprosma acerosa\nImage:Passiflora tetrandra by Nina Jones ac125.jpg|Passiflora tetrandra\nImage:Orthoceras solandri by Nina Jones ac142.jpg|Orthoceras solandri\nImage:Celmisia dallii by Nina Jones ac137.jpg|Celmisia dallii\nImage:Discaria toumatou by Nina Jones ac129.jpg|Discaria toumatou\nImage:Leucopogon fasciculatus by Nina Jones ac100.jpg|Leucopogon fasciculatus\nImage:Veronica hulkeana by Nina Jones AC110.jpg|Veronica hulkeana\nImage:Myosotis Monroi by Nina Jones ac115.jpg|Myosotis Monroi\nImage:Arthropodium candidum by Nina Jones ac112.jpg|Arthropodium candidum\nImage:Leptospermum scopatium by Nina Jones ac135.jpg|Leptospermum scoparium\nImage:Hoheria by Nina Jones a